  serving size: 781
time required: 40 minutes
servings: 2
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Trim the @aubergine{1} then halve lengthways. Chop each half into four long strips then chop widthways into roughly 2cm pieces. Pop on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{drizzle} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until the aubergine is soft in the middle and golden at the edge, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}) and @ginger{1}. Quarter the @chestnut mushrooms{150%g}. Chop the @potato{1} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel!).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the mushrooms and a pinch of salt and pepper. Stir and cook until the mushrooms are browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the onion, stir together and cook until softened, another ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic, ginger, @tomato puree{30%g} and @North Indian style spice mix{1}. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour in the @coconut milk{400%ml} and @water for the sauce{75%ml}. Stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1} and the potato. Bring to the boil, cover with a #lid{} and simmer until the potato is cooked, ~{20-25%minutes}. Stir every few minutes.

> Tip: The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

While the curry cooks, drain and rinse the @lentils{1} in a #sieve{}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1%handful}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Halve the @lime{1/2}. Once the curry is cooked and the potato tender, add in the lentils and roasted aubergine and bring back to the boil. Stir in half the coriander.

Squeeze in half the lime juice, then taste and add more lime juice, salt and pepper if you feel it needs it. Serve in #bowls{} with the remaining coriander sprinkled on top. Enjoy!